      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The metabolic cost of anaerobic glycolysis is indeed a critical aspect of the \"burn\" phenomenon. The buildup of lactic acid is a temporary consequence of the intense energy demands placed on the muscles.\n\nThe body has a few mechanisms to clear out the lactic acid and restore the normal functioning of the muscle cells. One of the primary mechanisms is the removal of lactic acid through the bloodstream. The lactic acid is transported to the liver, where it's converted back into glucose through a process called gluconeogenesis. This glucose is then released back into the bloodstream, where it can be used by other tissues or stored for later use.\n\nAnother mechanism is the removal of lactic acid through the kidneys. The kidneys filter the lactic acid from the blood and excrete it in the urine. This process is more efficient when the body is in a state of rest or recovery, as opposed to during intense exercise.\n\nIn terms of the metabolic cost, the anaerobic glycolysis process is relatively inexpensive in terms of energy expenditure. The energy required to generate ATP through anaerobic glycolysis is about 2-3 ATP per glucose molecule, whereas the energy required to generate ATP through oxidative phosphorylation (with oxygen) is about",
